    {
      "id": 9,
      "type": "Note",
      "pos": [
        420,
        1520
      ],
      "size": [
        700,
        420
      ],
      "flags": {},
      "order": 12,
      "mode": 0,
      "properties": {
        "text": ""
      },
      "widgets_values": [
        "MULTI-ANGLE PATCH - CALIBRATION PROOF (now with occlusion-mask precheck)\n\nThe LoRA angles are ABSOLUTE (subject-relative), NOT relative to your\nsource view. So set BOTH views on the Add Patch View node:\n  source_azimuth_view = what your source photo already is (front view\n    for a straight-on shot);  patch_*_view = what you asked the LoRA for\n    (must match the Qwen Multiangle Camera node exactly).\n  Orbit applied = patch - source.\n\n1. Generate a novel view at 'front-right quarter view / eye-level shot /\n   medium shot' (Qwen-Image-Edit-2511 + Multiple-Angles LoRA, e.g. via\n   ComfyUI-qwenmultiangle). Load it in the Patch novel view node.\n2. On Add Patch View keep patch_azimuth_view = 'front-right quarter view'\n   and source_azimuth_view = 'front view' (=> +45 deg orbit).\n3. Queue, then in the Atlas Viewport: Camera View, then Project.\n   GO/NO-GO: orbit slightly right - the patch should fill the primary's\n   occluded/grazing right side and stay aligned in the overlap. If it\n   lands on the WRONG side, tick flip_azimuth. If features line up,\n   constructed-orbit == LoRA-angle holds and the 3-patch build is safe.\n   (Needs a ComfyUI restart to load the new node + a browser refresh.)\n\nNEW - Atlas Occlusion Mask precheck (nodes to the right of the novel-view\nLoadImage, below the relief-mesh export):\n  CRITICAL: AtlasOcclusionMask's named-view widgets\n  (patch_azimuth_view/patch_elevation_view/patch_distance/\n  source_azimuth_view/source_elevation_view/flip_azimuth) are set\n  IDENTICAL to Add Patch View's — they independently reconstruct the SAME\n  orbit camera. If you change the angle on one node, change it on the\n  other too, or the mask will describe a different view than the patch\n  actually uses.\n  - Before judging the Add Patch View / Project result, check the\n    Occlusion Mask preview: WHITE should land on grazing walls, the\n    backside, and anything outside the primary photo's frame - exactly\n    where you'd expect the recovered camera couldn't have seen from this\n    new angle. The Coverage Mask preview should look like its exact\n    inverse.\n  - The novel-view image now flows through ImageCompositeMasked before\n    reaching Add Patch View. Here that composite is a PLACEHOLDER\n    (destination and source are both the same novel-view image, so it's\n    a no-op) - it only proves the wiring runs end-to-end. Swap in a\n    genuinely different destination/source image later (e.g. an\n    independently inpainted/refined version) to make the mask actually\n    select between two candidates instead of compositing an image with\n    itself."
      ]
    },
